article.description:
Jessica Brungo scored 19 points and No. 8 Penn State remained unbeaten in Big Ten play with a 60-59 victory
over Wisconsin on Sunday.
article.headline: Brungo scores 19 points
article.linkText: Wisconsin rallies, but Penn State takes the win
article.story:
MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Rene Portland placed more importance on a
conference win than some sloppy play down the stretch by her Penn
State team.

Jessica Brungo scored 19 points and Penn State (No. 8 ESPN/USA Today, No. 9 AP) won its
fourth straight game, 60-59 over Wisconsin in a Big Ten matchup
Sunday.

"We're certainly pleased with any Big Ten win, to be quite
honest," Portland said after the Lady Lions (11-3, 4-0) survived a
late rally.

Kelly Mazzante added 15 points, including a pair of key free
throws in the final minute for the Lions. Mazzante needs 27 points
to tie the Big Ten career scoring record of 2,578 points set by
Ohio State's Katie Smith from 1992-96.

Mazzante was just 4-of-19 from the field and missed 13 of her
last 14 shots.

"I thought they pressured (me) pretty well, but I did have some
open looks," Mazzante said. "I was short all night. My shots just
weren't falling.

With 19 seconds left, Mazzante hit a pair of key free throws to
give Penn State a 60-56 lead after Wisconsin went on a 13-2 run and
closed within two.

Lello Gebisa made a 3-pointer with 3.8 seconds left as the
Badgers closed within 60-59, but Mazzante took the inbounds pass
and dribbled out the clock.

"It was too little, too late and it's unfortunate," Wisconsin
coach Lisa Stone said.

Gebisa and Ashley Josephson scored 13 points each to lead
Wisconsin (5-7, 0-3), which was 9-of-14 from 3-point range.

The Badgers, who have lost four straight, never led and trailed
by as many as 16 points midway through the first half.

"We could have folded our tents but we competed," Stone said.
"We fought and clawed back."

Wisconsin used an 11-0 run to pull within 41-39 with 13 minutes
remaining.

The Badgers were within 43-41 with 12:18 left but were held
without a basket for 6:25.

The Lady Lions took advantage, scoring 11 straight points to
push their lead to 54-41 with 6:26 left.

That set the stage for Wisconsin's final surge, which included
3-pointers by four players.

After pulling within 58-51 with 2:48 left on a basket by Lello
Gebisa, the Badgers turned the ball over on four straight
possessions.

Wisconsin finished the game with 21 turnovers.

Tanisha Wright had 13 points and Ashli Schwab 11 for Penn State.
Jess Strom had nine assists for the Lady Lions.
